{{Spanish name|Mazurkiewicz|Iglesias}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Ladislao Mazurkiewicz | image = Mazurkiewicz, Porta, Morena 1974.jpg | image_size = 250 | caption = Mazurkiewicz (left), [[Roberto Porta|Porta]] and [[Fernando Morena|Morena]] | fullname = Ladislao Mazurkiewicz Iglesias | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1945|02|14}} | birth_place = [[Piriápolis]], [[Uruguay]] | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2013|01|02|1945|02|14}} | death_place = [[Montevideo]], Uruguay | height = {{height|m=1.79}} | position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]] | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = 1963–1964 | clubs1 = [[Racing Club de Montevideo|RC Montevideo]] | caps1 = | goals1 = | years2 = 1964–1971 | clubs2 = [[C.A. Peñarol|Peñarol]] | caps2 = | goals2 = | years3 = 1971–1974 | clubs3 = [[Atlético Mineiro]] | caps3 = 44 | goals3 = 0 | years4 = 1974–1975 | clubs4 = [[Granada CF|Granada]] | caps4 = 2 | goals4 = 0 | years5 = 1976–1978 | clubs5 = [[Cobreloa]] | caps5 = | goals5 = | years6 = 1979–1980 | clubs6 = [[América de Cali]] | caps6 = 36 | goals6 = 0 | years7 = 1980–1981 | clubs7 = [[C.A. Peñarol|Peñarol]] | caps7 = | goals7 = | totalcaps = | totalgoals = | nationalyears1 = 1965–1974 | nationalteam1 = [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] | nationalcaps1 = 36 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | manageryears1 = 1988–1989 | managerclubs1 = [[C.A. Peñarol|Peñarol]] | medaltemplates = | club-update = | nationalteam-update = }} '''Ladislao Mazurkiewicz Iglesias'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/j/j5664.html |title=Mazurkiewicz, Ladislao Mazurkiewicz Iglesias |publisher=BDFutbol |date=1945-02-14 |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> ({{IPA-es|laðizˈlao masuɾˈkjeβitʃ|am}}; 14 February 1945 – 2 January 2013) was a [[Uruguay]]an [[association football|football]] [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] of the 1960s and 1970s.
==Career== Mazurkiewicz helped the [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay national team]] qualify for the semifinals of the [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970 World Cup]], where the ''charrúas'' were stopped by the eventual champion, [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]. He was elected the best goalkeeper of that tournament. He also played for the Brazilian side [[Atlético Mineiro]].
During his international career (1965–74), he earned a total of 36 appearances with the national team of his native Uruguay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/uru-recintlp.html |title=Uruguay - Record International Players |publisher=Rsssf.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628200526/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/uru-recintlp.html |archivedate=2011-06-28 |df= }}</ref> He coached [[C.A. Peñarol|Peñarol]] from 1988–89.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://girasolweb.tripod.com/tecnicos.htm |title=Tecnicos |publisher=Girasolweb.tripod.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref>
==Personal life== Mazurkiewicz's father was [[Poles|Polish]] and his mother [[Spain|Spanish]]. Though of Polish ancestry, he did not know [[Polish language|Polish]] and never visited [[Poland]].<ref>[http://www.rp.pl/artykul/60511,965827.html Zmarł słynny bramkarz Ladislao Mazurkiewicz] at ''[[Rzeczpospolita (newspaper)|Rzeczpospolita]]'', 2 January 2013.</ref>
==Death== Mazurkiewicz died on 2 January 2013 in [[Montevideo, Uruguay]], aged 67, from undisclosed causes. He is buried at [[Parque del Recuerdo (Uruguay)|Parque del Recuerdo]] cemetery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elobservador.com.uy/noticia/240425/fallecio-ladislao-mazurkiewicz-una-leyenda-del-futbol-uruguayo/|title=Falleció Ladislao Mazurkiewicz, una leyenda del fútbol uruguayo|publisher=[[El Observador (Uruguay)|El Observador]]|date=2 January 2013|accessdate=2 January 2013|language=es}}</ref>
